2022-01-19 18:47:11	vd	does arch uses a custom /init or does it rely on systemd service units?
2022-01-19 18:47:30	<--	sogens (~Sogens@23.81.114.219) has quit (Client Quit)
2022-01-19 18:47:30	-->	sbradnick [sbradnick] (Scott Bradnick) (~sbradnick@user/sbradnick) has joined #archlinux
2022-01-19 18:47:48	-->	sogens [sogens] (Jason Fischmann) (~Sogens@23.81.114.219) has joined #archlinux
2022-01-19 18:47:55	Earnestly	vd: It uses systemd
2022-01-19 18:47:59	angerctl	by default it's a custom init but you can use systemd, too
2022-01-19 18:48:14	angerctl	oh, wait, i was thinking about the initramfs, nvm
2022-01-19 18:48:22	grawity	the default initramfs /init from mkinitcpio is a busybox ash script, but systemd is available; the default rootfs /sbin/init is always systemd
2022-01-19 18:48:34	-->	packer [Packer] (The Lounge User) (~packer@static.228.10.251.148.clients.your-server.de) has joined #archlinux
2022-01-19 18:48:50	!=	angerctl is now known as Namarrgon
2022-01-19 18:49:49	<--	lionkor (~lionkor@beammp/staff/lionkor) has quit (Ping timeout: 240 seconds)
2022-01-19 18:49:58	<--	beastDiv1 (~beastDivi@user/beastdivision) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2022-01-19 18:50:05	vd	the only thing that systemd needs in order to be in intrd mode (and thus reach initrd.target) is to have /init linked to the systemd binary as well as an /etc/initrd-release file, correct?
2022-01-19 18:50:40	grawity	I think so,
2022-01-19 18:50:57	grawity	but see build() in /usr/lib/initcpio/install/systemd for how Arch sets it up (if enabled)
